[This case in New Hampshire, is not surprising since it occurred within the geographical range of EEE virus in the eastern USA, where human and equine cases occur sporadically. As is usual, there are many more equine than human cases.

There was a recent case in New Hampshire involving a mule (see ProMED archive no 20140906.2752704) and a non-fatal human case cited in the above report (see ProMED archive no 20140823.2717174). The virus is maintained in passerine birds and transmitted among them by the black-tailed mosquito, _Culiseta melanura_. The species occasionally feeds on mammals and may have been the bridge transmitter in the above case.

There is a vaccine commercially available for equine administration but not for humans. Clinical cases in humans are very serious, with a case fatality rate of 33 per cent and significant neurological sequelae in survivors (see http://www.cdc.gov/EasternEquineEncephalitis/). It is prudent to follow the recommendations above to avoid mosquito bites. [Particularly in areas where equine cases have been reported. - Mod.JW]

A map showing the location of Carroll County, where Conway, NH is located can be accessed at http://geology.com/county-map/new-hampshire-county-map.gif and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail map showing the location of New Hampshire in the northeastern USA at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2813455,41140. - Mod.TY]
